  "signature": "ed25519:b1c3e5a7f9d2b4c6e8a0c2d4f6b8e0a2c4d6f8b0e2a4c6d8f0b2e4a6c8d0f2b4",
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-noncannulated-2026-04",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team accepts the FEA model for use in the stated COU (prediction of ASTM F1717 static compression-bending performance of the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct) with the following documented basis and acknowledged limitations. All three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) pass both pre-established acceptance criteria: mean QoI differences of 1.1–1.5% (threshold <10%) and E/uval values of 0.54–0.72 (threshold <1.96). These results hold across all three ensemble FEA implementations (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes), providing cross-laboratory computational confirmation. The team explicitly acknowledges that evidence confidence is assessed at approximately 50% on several factors, primarily driven by: (1) limited experimental sample size (N=11), which yields statistical power of ~52% for detecting a 10% QoI difference; (2) high experimental coefficient of variation (CV 9.2–10.4%) reflecting inherent construct-to-construct variability; and (3) single test condition (ASTM F1717 standard protocol only), resulting in the Test conditions factor achieving level 2 against a required level 3. These limitations are documented honestly and transparently throughout the evidence record; no attempt has been made to inflate confidence scores or suppress uncertainty information. The wide prediction intervals (up to ±18% for stiffness, approaching the 10% bound for force at 40 mm) are explicitly reported. The team's acceptance judgment rests on the following reasoning: (a) the mean predictions are well within acceptance bounds with E/uval well below 1.96, indicating that even accounting for quantified uncertainty the model is not inconsistent with experiment; (b) the COU is explicitly scoped to the F1717 standard protocol condition, so the single-condition limitation does not constitute an out-of-scope extrapolation; (c) model risk level 3 with medium decision consequence and medium model influence places this assessment in a regime where the documented evidence base, despite its acknowledged width, is sufficient to support a regulatory submission with appropriate disclosure; (d) the 12 of 13 factors at or above required level, with the one shortfall (Test conditions) explicitly bounded by COU scope, represents an acceptable credibility profile for a Class II device submission. The team recommends that future work increase experimental N to ≥20 and include at least one additional test condition (e.g., elevated temperature or alternative loading rate) to elevate the Test conditions factor to required level 3 and increase evidence confidence above 70%.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
